@flexiarg peeragogy/carrying-capacity
@title Match Engagement to What the Group and the Person Can Sustain
@keywords burnout, over-contribution, dominance, sustainability, throttling, stepping-back
@audience peer-learning facilitators, contributors
@tone practical
@style process-pattern
@references [peeragogy/heartbeat peeragogy/moderation peeragogy/roles]

! conclusion: A peer-learning group has a finite carrying capacity for any one participant's contribution rate, and any one participant has a finite carrying capacity for the project.  Sustained over-contribution by some, or under-contribution by others, will distort the group's dynamics and burn people out.  The pattern is to recognise the asymmetry in real time and adjust — by stepping back, by inviting others in, by reducing one's own pace, or by reshaping the work so it costs less to enter.
  + context: Peer-learning groups attract uneven engagement.  Some contributors take on disproportionate load; others lurk, intend to contribute, and never enter; energetic participants railroad ideas; reflective participants go silent.  These are not individual failings — they are predictable dynamics of voluntary co-production.  Carrying capacity asks each participant and the group as a whole to keep these dynamics inside survivable bands rather than letting them run unchecked.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: individual momentum ↔ group sustainability.
    Real: high-momentum contributors keep the project alive in the short term; the same momentum, sustained, can crowd out the participation that makes the project peer-driven in the first place.  Both effects are real and operate simultaneously.
    Irreducible: a group cannot maximise both individual contribution rates and balanced participation.  At any given moment one is being prioritised over the other; the question is whether the trade is conscious.
    Active: the pull recurs whenever a contributor feels burnout symptoms, whenever discussion patterns become one-directional, and whenever a roadmap revision exposes who has been carrying which load.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Step back, observe: a high-contributing participant deliberately reduces their pace and watches the dynamics that emerge in the space they leave.  This is diagnostic before it is corrective.
    (2) Ask, then listen: replace assertion with question — "what do others think?" — and accept that the answer may be a longer silence than the assertive participant would have tolerated.
    (3) Reshape the entry cost: rather than only modulating one's own behaviour, change the project so others can join cheaply — clearer explanations, smaller first tasks, a more legible roadmap.
    (4) Name the role-change: when stepping back temporarily, tell whoever holds the facilitation role.  This protects the group from interpreting absence as drift.
    (5) Renegotiate the goal: revisit the roadmap and confirm what concrete goal the group is moving toward, since over- and under-contribution often track to ambiguity about what counts as progress.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: contributors notice their own and others' load and adjust before the dynamics ossify; participation distributes across the group rather than concentrating on a few.  Failing when: the same names appear on every contribution thread, or a participant is operating well past their sustainable rate without anyone naming it.
  + ABSENCE-SIGNALS:
    - Burnout cascade: a high-contributor exits abruptly and the project stalls because no one was tracking their load.
    - Power-law lock-in: the engagement distribution flattens into "the same five people forever" with no ramp for others.
    - Silent dissent: under-contributors disagree but do not say so, because the cost of entering the conversation has grown too high.
    - Roadmap drift: the project's stated goal and its actual concentration of effort diverge without anyone surfacing the gap.
